**Item #:** SCP-9161

**Object Class:** Safe

**Special Containment Procedures:** Instances of SCP-9161 are to be seized and placed in Anomalous Objects Storage at Site-88 for standard research procedures. Foundation webcrawlers are to index secondhand clothing storefront websites and scan product images for patterns matching SCP-9161's design. Foundation item retrieval teams are to be immediately dispatched on discovery of SCP-9161 instances sold with "fair" or "as is" condition.

**Description:** SCP-9161 is a line of women’s shoes by designer Marcelo Brunelleschi manufactured between 1982 and 1986. When a pair of SCP-9161 are worn, a neurological link between the shoes and the wearer is formed so that any damage to the shoe manifests as a temporary lesion of the brain at a topographically corresponding site. When the shoes are removed, the wearer regains all mental and neurological faculties.

All contained SCP-9161 instances were seized together from a leather deadstock warehouse; supply chain manifests found at the site confirm this collection to be the majority of extant instances. Most instances had been packaged for mail-order before mass recall. An estimated 70 pairs remain in circulation worldwide.

**Testing Log:** All tests were conducted on a single subject, D-20398, with the approval of the Ethics Committee. 

The subject was supplied a helmet and ankle braces to protect from falls. Tests were halted immediately upon evidence of endangerment or emotional distress. Tests were not at risk of inducing physical pain, as the brain is devoid of nociceptors. Distress was assessed by a researcher observing the testing chamber from an adjacent booth, since in several lesion states the subject was unable to self-report. 


||~ Lesion Site on Shoes ||~ Observed Effects ||~ Conclusion ||
|| Vamp, 1 cm bilateral superficial incisions || The subject stood motionless until told to walk the length of the testing chamber. All instructions were followed without query or protest. When asked questions, the subject replied with flat affect in single words. || Loss of executive function substantiates map to prefrontal cortex, consistent with established cortical topography. All effects reversed upon test end.  ||
|| Left lower throat, single incision || The subject walked when prompted to but displayed marked difficulty responding verbally to questions. The subject's speech was effortful and halting.[[footnote]]Transcript excerpt: "Yes... yes... yes... yes... yes..."[[/footnote]] || Consistent with established topography, loss of speech generation substantiates map to Broca's area. All effects reversed upon test end. ||
|| Topline, notches made from left to right side of the shoe. Both symmetrical and asymmetrical scoring across shoes tested. || The subject did not respond to pressure or temperature stimuli at the area corresponding to the lesioned region. Scoring on left shoe caused numbness on right area of the body, and vice versa. Walking was obstructed only when lesions interfered with leg and foot sensation. When notches were made 2 mm toward the toe box, the subject became unable to move the corresponding limb. The subject collapsed if the lesioned areas corresponded to the trunk, legs, or feet.|| Somatosensory region map substantiated. Contralateral body representation substantiated with ipsilateral hemispheric map. All effects reversed upon test end. All subsequent tests assume bilaterality. ||
|| Heel, 2 cm of material removed || The subject collapsed and lost consciousness. Respiration and pulse ceased. || Midbrain/brainstem map substantiated. SCP-9161 was immediately removed from the subject, after which all effects were reversed. As expected, the subject made a full, immediate recovery. The subject's helmet was replaced. ||
|| Upper counter, punctures || The subject reported loss of sight. The subject walked for two steps before losing balance and falling to the floor, where the subject remained for the remainder of the test. Pupillary response was normal. || Visual cortex map substantiated. All effects reversed upon test end. ||
|| Lower counter, punctures || When instructed to walk, the subject’s gait was staggering and unsteady. The subject lost balance after five steps and fell over. The subject attempted to walk again and completed seven steps before falling over. The subject crawled for the remainder of the test. || Cerebellar region map substantiated. All effects reversed upon test end. ||
|| No lesions || Footage rendered fully. See below. || See below. ||

[[div class="blockquote" style="border-radius: 10px; margin: 10px"]]
+++ TEST #8 VIDEO LOG
Timestamps collected from Camera 1, set behind the observation window. Camera 2 is floor-level.
> [BEGIN LOG]
> 
> **00:00:** The subject enters the frame wearing SCP-9161 and stands, waiting for instruction.
> 
> **00:05:** @@[@@//Intercom: "Walk to the far wall."//] The subject walks. Gait is normal and unhurried. @@[@@//Camera 2 tracks SCP-9161 for the length of the walk. Audio: The clicks of the heels are evenly spaced.//]
> 
> **00:22:** The subject reaches the far wall. She stands facing the far wall. Her fingers twitch. She shifts her weight from one foot to the other.
> 
> **00:31:** She turns and faces the observation window.
> 
> **00:34:** She locates Camera 1. Eye contact is established and sustained. She does not blink.
> 
> **00:45:** Subject: "Hello." @@[@@//Pause.//] "What are you looking for?"
> 
> **00:48:** She remains still. Eye contact remains unbroken for a further twenty seconds.
> 
> **01:08:** She blinks. She bends slowly and reaches for her right heel. @@[@@//Camera 2 tracks the gesture.//]
>  
> **01:12:** She slides two fingers between the heel and her foot and draws the shoe off. @@[@@//Camera 2. Audio: The leather creaks. A small wet sound issues as the toes unstick and separate.//] The shoe dangles from her fingertips as her foot touches the floor.
> 
> **01:18:** She picks up her left foot and removes the left shoe in a similar manner. She sets the pair upright on the floor, side by side. She rises and stands beside them, barefoot. @@[@@//Audible respiration.//]
> 
> **01:30:** The subject stands. She continues to face the window. No instruction is given. She does not move for eleven seconds, save for slight twitches in her fingers.
> 
> **01:41:** She reaches for the helmet clasp beneath her chin. 
> 
> **01:41:** @@[@@//Intercom: "Put the shoes on. Walk back to where you started."//]
> 
> **01:42:** The subject immediately moves to put on SCP-9161. 
> 
> **01:46:** @@[@@//Camera 2 tracks the object.//] The subject crosses the chamber. Gait is normal.
> 
> **02:03:** The subject reaches the chamber entrance and turns around. The subject waits for instruction.
> 
> [END LOG]
**Conclusion:** SCP-9161 removal at 01:18 produced no measurable effect. Baseline confirmed.
